<span class="displaytext"><b>for immediate release<br/>contact:</b> kevin madden (857) 288-6390 <p><b>boston, ma –</b> today, (candidate last) for president launched its newest television ad, "take charge." the ad highlights governor (candidate last)'s record of enforcing our immigration laws and opposing efforts to increase the benefits for illegal immigration. as president, governor (candidate last) will work to secure our border, reform our immigration system and fight sanctuary policies. </p><p>the ad will begin airing as part of the campaign's rotation today in iowa and new hampshire. script and viewing links are below. </p><p><b> <u>script for "take charge" (tv:30):</u> </b> </p><p><b>announcer:</b> "illegal immigration – we need smart, tough solutions, not just talk. </p><p>"what will it take to fix it? technology, new ideas, guts, values – (candidate full). </p><p>"he said no to driver's licenses for illegals; no to in-state tuition; fought for english in the classroom. </p><p>"the only candidate with a proven record of fixing the big problems. </p><p>"from day one: (candidate full) will do what he does best – take charge, demand results, no excuses." </p><p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "i'm (candidate full) and i approve this message." </p><p><em>to watch "take charge," please see:</em> <a href="http://tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=474548">http://tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=474548</a> </p><p><b> <u>ad facts: script for "take charge" (tv:30):</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "illegal immigration – we need smart, tough solutions, not just talk. what will it take to fix it? technology, new ideas, guts, values – (candidate full). he said no to driver's licenses for illegals; no to in-state tuition; fought for english in the classroom." </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- governor (candidate last) opposed the issuance of driver's licenses to illegal immigrants.</b> "'those who are here illegally should not receive tacit support from our government that gives an indication of legitimacy,' the governor said, echoing arguments that opponents have voiced in the commonwealth and in other states considering similar license measures. 'if they are here illegally, they should not get driver's licenses,' he said." (scott s. greenberger, "(candidate last) stand dims chances of license for undocumented," <em>the boston globe</em>, 10/28/03) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) vetoed in-state tuition for illegal immigrants.</b> "(candidate last) also vetoed a number of outside sections of the budget, including:...a plan that would have permitted illegal aliens to pay the same in-state tuition rate at our public colleges and universities as massachusetts citizens." (office of the governor, "(candidate last) signs $22.402b fiscal year 2005 'no new tax' budget," press release, 6/25/04) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last):</b> "i hate the idea of in any way making it more difficult for kids, even those who are illegal aliens, to afford college in our state. ... but equally, perhaps a little more than equally, i do not want to create an incentive to do something which is illegal." (scott s. greenberger and raphael lewis, "(candidate last) vetoes $108.5m in budget," <em>the</em> <em>boston globe</em>, 6/26/04) </p><p><b>- governor (candidate last) fought efforts to weaken massachusetts' english immersion law.</b> "but yesterday, (candidate last) press secretary shawn feddeman said the governor will fight all attempts to slow the implementation of english immersion, known on the ballot as question 2. ... 'he will veto anything that weakens or delays english immersion,' feddeman said." (anand vaishnav, "(candidate last) firm on english timetable," <em>the boston globe</em>, 1/24/03) </p></blockquote> <p><b>announcer:</b> "the only candidate with a proven record of fixing the big problems. from day one: (candidate full) will do what he does best – take charge, demand results, no excuses." <b>governor (candidate full):</b> "i'm (candidate full) and i approve this message." </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- governor (candidate last) has "a solid reputation in the business community for turning companies around."</b> cnn's rhonda schaffler: "(candidate last) had a solid reputation in the business community for turning companies around, like staples, domino's pizza and the sports authority." (cnn's "business unusual," 1/27/02) </p><p><b>- <em>the associated press</em>:</b> "(candidate last) took over as head of salt lake's olympic organizing committee in february 1999 after it was revealed salt lake organizers doled out more than $1 million in cash and gifts to members of the international olympic committee to win the 2002 bid. under (candidate last)'s leadership, the games were lauded as a critical success, a model of post-sept. 11 security and turned a $100 million profit. (candidate last), a successful venture capitalist before the games, wrote a book after titled 'turnaround: crisis, leadership and the olympic games.'" (debbie hummel, "utah's 'adopted son' returns to state for presidential fundraiser," <em>the associated press</em>, 2/21/07) </p><p><b>- in massachusetts, governor (candidate last) closed a nearly $3 billion shortfall without raising taxes.</b> "when (candidate full) became governor of massachusetts in 2003, the state had a budget gap of almost $3 billion and was losing thousands of jobs a month. in mr. (candidate last)'s four-year tenure, the deficit was eliminated without raising the sales tax or the income tax, and since the labor slump hit bottom in december 2003, the state has gained 81,000 jobs." (pam belluck, "(candidate last) candidacy puts massachusetts economy in spotlight," <em>the new york times</em>, 3/16/07) </p><p><b>- <em>the weekly standard</em>'s terry eastland:</b> "as governor, (candidate last) has scored another turnaround, conservative in both ends and means. told during the campaign that he would inherit a deficit of between $500 million and $1.5 billion, (candidate last) discovered upon taking office a $650 million deficit in fiscal 2003 and an anticipated one of $3 billion in fiscal 2004. (candidate last) balanced the 2003 budget, and he finished 2004 with a $700 million surplus. a reviving economy helped, but (candidate last) didn't tax or borrow, and he reduced spending through government consolidation and reform." (terry eastland, "in 2008, will it be mormon in america?" <em>the weekly standard</em>, 6/6/05) </p></blockquote> <p><em>to watch "take charge," please see:</em> <a href="http://tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=474548">http://tv.(candidate full).com/?showid=474548</a></p></span>



